      <div data-bk-layout="pad:0  middle">
        <div data-bk-layout="palm:6" data-bk-links="secondary fade underline-hover" class="user-content  font-light  font-m">
          <p>Basekit is a custom frontend “framework” built over many years for FortyTwo’s client projects. It's freely available for anyone to use but be aware that we offer no warranty or formal support.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>


  <div class="bg-white  pad">
    <div class="site-container">
      {# DEV NOTE: Should be editable from the CMS home edit page #}
      <h3 data-bk-layout="pad:rl" class="font-xl  font-bold">Getting started</h3>

      <div data-bk-layout="pad:trl  lap:8" data-bk-links="primary underline fade exit" class="user-content">
        <p>This Basekit project makes key use of <a href="http://gulpjs.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Gulp</a>, <a href="http://sass-lang.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Sass</a> and <a href="https://twig.sensiolabs.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Twig</a> amongst the usual suspects such as NPM and Git. We build static frontend templates in Twig so that can be ported later on to Craft CMS, however the core framework Sass does not require Twig to be used.</p>

        <p>You’ll also want a local server of some kind, we currently prefer <a href="https://laravel.com/docs/5.4/valet" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Laravel Valet</a> for small static sites and initial frontend templating, like this.</p>

        <p>Once you've downloaded this repo, cd to the directory and run <code>$ npm install</code> to get the required Gulp packages.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

